Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A mental institution where young people meet today.
A tomb chapel where the subway tunnel is being dug.
Small-scale farmers are farming the land that used to be farmers' land.
The oldest official map of Munich reveals exciting stories.
It's annoying when maps aren't up to date.
Anyone who's ever had to get upset because the car navigator showed a green meadow instead of a bypass road knows that.
The historical maps of the Bavarian Digital Atlas, a service of the Bavarian State Government's geoportal, are far from up-to-date - but precisely for this reason they are very informative.
Especially when you compare them to current online maps.
This will show how cities and communities in the Munich Mercury area have changed since the 19th century.
The Bavarian digital atlas is a patchwork of paper that is not immediately recognizable as such.
The large overview map has been supplemented by more detailed maps for cities and municipalities, called "Urposition Sheets".
These were created between 1810 and 1864 according to the information provided by the Bavarian Survey Office and are the result of the first survey of Bavaria.
Your client is Napoleon.
The French army leader occupied Bavaria from the spring of 1800 during the Second War of Coalition with Austria.
Napoleon wanted to get an overview of the occupied territory and commissioned a topographic survey of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Even though the French troops finally withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville of 9 February 1801, it was the present-day neighbours who created the idea of a land-wide Bavarian map.
The project was continued by the Elector Max IV Joseph, who established the Topographical Bureau - the Bavarian Survey Office.
The original sheet for Munich dates from 1856 and can be found on the website of the Bavarian State Library, as can all other copies.
The comparison between then and now is most striking in the example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and grown together.
An example is the Underdog, which appears relatively isolated on the 1856 map.
Sendling was incorporated as a Munich district 21 years after the map was created, in 1877.
Today, Underdog is in the middle of the city.
The houses of the Undendlings are concentrated around 1856 along the present-day Plinganserstraße, which was only named in 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the Bavarian peasant uprising against Austria in 1705.
Where West Park is today, you see nothing but fields - at first glance, when you zoom in, you see a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers: hand-numbered floor pieces from the so-called "original record", from which the land tax was derived.
Small plots are no longer occupied by farmers - they are occupied by small gardeners of the "Land in the Sun" plant.
A large green area is visible north of Unterendling.
The Theresienwiese, which has been the site of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was in fact a meadow in the 19th century - not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives a glimpse into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the first page of the paper, you can read in the area of today's Au-Haidhausen district not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the hill "On the air" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstraße, people were once locked up with delusions.
In 1858/59 the Munich circle of madness "On the Heavens" was founded there.
From 1872 Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institution - the psychiatrist brought in connection with the death of King Ludwig II.
"He was progressive for his time, ending, for example, the chain of so-called lunatics.
He also forbade the staff to use violence against the inmates", says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Haidhausen Museum, who has been involved in an exhibition at the institution.
The hospital had initially accommodated 280 patients, but was later expanded to 500 seats.
At a certain point, this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the district hospital in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany, has been located there.
The former Auer Institute is now the meeting place of the Munich Salesianum.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training establishments.
To the west is the football field of TSV Munich East, to the east are residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's home "Casa Don Bosco" was built - in an architectural imitation of the original building of the madhouse, which was destroyed during bombing during World War II.
The Marienplatz was listed as "Hauptplatz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change in the heart of Munich.
In December 1944, Allied bombs tore many holes in the city center.
A large one remains today - at Marienhof.
The English Institute, small business houses and a medieval tomb chapel once stood at Marienhof, where the preliminary work is being done and on 5 April 2017 the spanning of the second S-Bahn main line.
The slider allows comparison of the old Munich map with the air view of today - and fills the hole at Marienhof.
Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning for people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, scheduled to take effect on August 28, 2017, urges African American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to exercise extreme caution and caution when traveling through the state, due to a series of questionable racially-based incidents that have occurred throughout the state recently and are noted here", the group's statement said.
A recent Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as state law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"You have civil rights violations that people are going through.
They are stopped because of the color of their skin, they are beaten or killed", said the president of the Missouri NAACP, Rod Chapel, to the Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints at a frequency we have never heard before".
It's the first such warning the organization has issued for a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist abuse against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while traveling across the state and being taken into custody by Missouri State Police without being charged with a crime.
The Council also points to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's Office, which shows that black motorists are stopped 75 percent more often in the state than whites.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and inform their families, friends and coworkers about what could happen in Missouri", Chapel said.
"People have to be prepared to bring bail or let relatives know they're traveling across the state".
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's Hate Crimes Reporting Program, which ranks the state 16th in the nation in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after the states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently, interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
