Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now the Trump White House is taking over the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
The Americans value it as much as any other - hence the carefully orchestrated overthrow of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump regime, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic ax in a heated argument with CNN's Jim Acosta over the president's proposals to drastically restrict legal immigration to the Statue of Liberty.
To be fair, Miller didn't attack the statue himself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he had done it.
But he attacked its significance, and in particular the significance attributed to it, when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed.
As Miller said to Acosta, "I don't want to go into a whole thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is ... a symbol of American freedom that enlightens the world.
The poem you're referring to, which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty".
Miller is factually correct, but as he put it, it's not really about history.
It is about the contemporary resonance of Lazarus's stirring words, the only ones in which a state invites not just any old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Your tired, your poor, your oppressed masses, who long to breathe freely, the miserable waste of your rich coasts".
There's never been a better time to see the "miserable waste" on our screens.
Miller didn't engage in literary criticism -- he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's United States.
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural debate: it is indeed a conflict over the meaning of America.
Lazarus and her friends, who were working to get her words out to the base after she died, knew full well that they were doing something highly political.
The sculpture was intended to show the connections between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classic pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: In her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has been given a voice.
And she gives herself a very different name: Mother of the Exile.
The poem's association with the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nationalism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the people on the right wing have long wanted to change that back.
The great scribe Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist for Trump's coming, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty was not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative bringing the American flame to the overnight world: "Lady Liberty is moving forward.
She's supposed to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not to light the way to the United States".
Quite unusual, Limbaugh came across something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of the point of view of perception.
The great imaginative act of Lazarus was to see him as he was seen by the exhausted, miserable but hopeful people after long and often terrible journeys on the decks of ships.
It's really about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they need to hear.
And that's not the perspective that Miller and Trump would ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is not to light the way, but to ignite the hatred that is their only source of power.
