Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand the heat of voters
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it wasn't long before the newspapers beat him up for everything from domestic policy to his political principles.
He was a bit of a scolding man, I'm sure.
But he didn't silence his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be taken away - and, dumb and dumb, we are led like sheep to the slaughter".
Which brings me to Maryland, where Governor Larry Hogan has to work on becoming more like Washington.
Hogan's staff blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online comment was full of a backlash with "So what?"
"It's just Facebook", many people said.
But it's important.
And it's especially important when it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in a vastly democratic state who is amazingly popular.
He has the second highest approval rating of the 50 governors in the nation.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in the leadership of his state and a strict adherence to principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as a primary means of connecting with his constituents and playing his hairless post-chemotherapy head on his page.
So blocking people who come to the governor's side - which is a public forum that is called official and is staffed by employees who are paid with public tax dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people who are whipping people online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur and a pastor, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not profane.
The priest quoted the Bible in his mail and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md., was not hateful, but she asked about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other current news", she wrote in the comment section of The Post.
"I also don't appreciate this idea, when a number of people take a stand on the same issue, they are dismissed by some as a so-called collective effort rather than recognized as a large group of concerned citizens".
What the governor's staff called a "concentrated spam attack" would probably be called "advocacy" by others.
The Facebook era makes it easy to cut a story by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It's much cleaner than in the past, if you'd done the same thing, that you sent employees to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials or arrest and silence protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for insulting Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who were blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones in this matter occurred last week in Virginia.
The chairwoman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she banned a voter from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also got a visit from the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
That shouldn't be so hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable port had a similar effect to the Internet.
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter writers followed his lead.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
The people who used pseudonyms like "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius", and "Portius" all wrote letters to newspapers denouncing Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticizing his position on the Amity Treaty, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Project's online papers.
But he didn't shut her up.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are the foundation of our nation.
And true leadership is about accepting that.
