Poverty and Death in the Indonesian Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use the stove.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai Regency in the troubled Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually places a sweet potato - locally called "nota" - directly in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tubers are removed and eaten with diligent, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also does her daily work, such as washing clothes with muddy water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most villagers are unemployed, and many drink heavily, and there are the soldiers here.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m"., she says.
It is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was absorbed in 1969 after a controversial referendum in Indonesia, when only 1,026 elders were to vote by publicly raising their hands before the occupying forces.
An existing movement for independence, which had revolted against Dutch rule, quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which maintains control of the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea comprising the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is boring, and the journey involves a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire and then a five-hour drive by car every morning.
There is no public transport.
The city of about 19,000 is made up of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated roofs that have been turned into various shades of yellow-brown by rust.
Very few Indonesians have made their way here, let alone journalists and virtually no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, pointing to her vibrant, hand-woven turban, dark shirt, and light skirt.
"We used to have only leaves on our bodies".
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28 percent of the population living below the poverty line and some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold country.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated $78 billion.
But this wealth is a source of misery for the Papuans, which ensures that Indonesia's powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
A 2005 New York Times investigation reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten these golden geese and are being treated with ruthlessness.
Activists say more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua's tribal lands in the 1970s were classified as genocide by the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
In the region alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
"We will lose everything", says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities from the previous year, such as unlawful executions and torture - rape and electrocution are particularly popular, according to another report - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week", says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened as Papua's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but demographic trends are changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warung canteens sell fried chicken and gadō gadō, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people are struggling to keep up.
"Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at the traditional market at a lower price than the local Papuans", explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, to work.
"It has cost the indigenous people of Papua - the Mama-Mama [women] of Papua - their market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised during his 2014 election campaign to address inequality and legal violations in Papua.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua's 29 districts - including Paniai - en route to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel cheated.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, expecting him to fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored", You says.
In fact, only two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October, Paniai suffered a low point.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols at a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke through the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on their lights.
One of the soldiers was offended by their sound and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers, who had been drinking, chased and beat the group with their rifle butts, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired at the group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government commission building was set on fire, and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and the military command center to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - running in circles and imitating a bird song - of Papua's Mee Pago tribe.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and military posts.
As the mood heated up, an internal radio message was sent to the soldiers: "If the masses resist more than three times, shoot them to death", according to an official TIME document, which was not released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto district of Enarotali, saw the imminent danger and called for calm and urged the crowd to return home.
No one was in the mood to listen.
"As I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist", he told TIME on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, lots of shots were fired", he adds.
Local man Alfius Youw was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", Yohanes, who like many Indonesians only has one name, told TIME in a gloomy mood.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him".
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers were only trying to "secure" their station because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us", said Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta 'filtered' until the following day.
For three weeks Jokowi made a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the historic wrongs in Papua.
"I want this case to be resolved immediately so that it will not happen again in the future", he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Wiranto said that he was establishing an extrajudicial mechanism to address historical human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
