New results of the Swedish Asylum Age Assessment Tests published
The latest results of tests on asylum seekers in Sweden who have undergone a new medical method of assessing their age show that more than 80 percent of those tested are over 18 years old.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started the tests last year.
They are to make the age assessment more accurate during the asylum procedure after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to assess the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in a further 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 years of age or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under 18 years of age".
The tests are only carried out in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent over the past few months.
"We don't see much difference in the statistics from the past months, the numbers are pretty constant", he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases where the person was assessed as over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests, saying that there were 442 cases that "suggest that the person being tested was 18 years of age or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that he would be 18 this year.
The method of medical ageing, in which wisdom teeth are x-rayed and knee joints are MRIed and then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
A skeptic is the Karolinska Institute endocrinologist Claude Marcus, whose work involves assessing the biological maturity of people to see whether they went through puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think that's the kind of measurement that should be used.
To judge biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can", he told Metro.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "Generally, you can say that the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is low.
The greatest risk is if the person is just under 18, in which case it is about 10 percent".
