Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to register, with further clinics to follow in October before it is rolled out across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a series of HIV medicines taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that there are just enough drugs in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such medications can be taken every day, about two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals, and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics will identify suitable participants who agree to the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People living in England and registered with a GP can also register for possible participation at their local participating sex clinic.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week following an international competitive procurement.
The study is designed to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how it is targeted, taken up and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and overtake the extensive and increasingly successful HIV prevention efforts.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of the greatest health challenges facing humanity".
Deborah Gold, chief executive of the National Aids Trust, said: "This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if targeted at the needy and vulnerable, offers the potential to change the UK HIV epidemic.
From September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individual controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, which will improve many, many lives.
We welcome this announcement".
Ian Green, chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now has to be to get the trial done quickly across the country and to ensure that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
