How did one activist learn the answer to the question, "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just one day after arriving in New York City, the St. Louis native was sitting on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she was renting and scrolling through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone in high school.
"The police just killed an 18-year-old, and it's still lying in the street", it said.
Confused that no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis-area rapper was tweeting live the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old who was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying on the street and would stay there for four hours.
"This is wild", Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put her phone down to go back to tweeting about people on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were pictures of the police band and people screaming, and a man claiming to be Brown's father, carrying a sign that read, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live feed of a policeman standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another cop unsecured his rifle and yelled, "I'm gonna kill you... animals all".
"That's not usual", Ferrell recalled her statement.
"This is not the kind of murder we're used to and can call typical".
At that moment, I felt a chill.
I was angry and I cried".
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two of them would leave for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?", in theaters starting on the 11th.
It's a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience, from the perspective of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell and her daughter, wearing a floral dress and a matching crown, drove to Ferguson, they discussed a conversation they had had countless times earlier this morning about the black experience and the black condition.
"Remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she remembered what she said.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it wasn't right.
I couldn't take her", Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is the culmination of what happened in the past.
She needs to know and see it and be raised to believe it.
It has to be well-developed, not just activism and organization, but also knowing the different layers of the black experience and the black constitution and what we need to do to become free, to free ourselves.
Even though I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn't personally experience blatant racism, she's no different than the next black woman's child.
I feel like I'd be doing her a disservice by keeping her away".
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a spot across from the police station that became a campground as the activists waited for the possible non-accusation of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who was making lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to protesters.
Slowly, a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism has changed completely after 9/11, " she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association, focusing on food justice and health inequality in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It's all come".
Weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar were just trying to "document" what happened.
One question came to Ferrell's mind: "Are you trying to document or are you trying to find a story that you can use?"
This skepticism has been fueled by countless cases of people, often white people, in a community that profited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan recently explained in an interview, "We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson didn't have their voices centered, and we wanted to do it differently".
Folayan had previously worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist in the field known for his activism around death row inmates.
His commitment brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals who followed the team of "Whose Streets?" in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or speaks to us. We talk", Davis said.
"That's the main thing for me, how these people are represented, because that's how I'm going to be represented".
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement is "not about a messianic leader, but about a community coming together", Folayan said - she turned out to be the most outspoken participant in the film.
As a result, documents from "Whose Streets?" reveal surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, how she falls in love and marries his wife.
"I felt like I was naked", Ferrell said, laughing as she first saw the finished product.
"But I've come to understand that there has to be a certain vulnerability in this work and in the humanization of black people".
Furthermore, Ferrell's story echoes the role of black lesbian women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who have been the subject of the film "BlacklivesMatter" on social media after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012, identify as gay.
"Black, gay women in leadership positions have been the driving force behind the movement as a whole", Ferrell said, "and so we're constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of it all".
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really sustained by black women and many black women".
She insists, however, that "this is not an affirmative type of action", where Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who stirred up that energy", she said.
"It's no coincidence that she was on the front lines, "because living at these intersections as a black, gay woman is so much at stake.
You can feel her energy through the screen".
The news cameras in Ferguson have long since disappeared, but the racial ties between the community and the police continue.
Ferrell is on probation for two and a half years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls home: "A chaos".
Yet she clings to a song and she feels bound to that memory ever since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains".
