A fitting resemblance: artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the room at the Fridman Gallery in New York, you can see many faces -- white, black, and brown, almost imperceptibly alike -- hanging from the ceiling on cables.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek swabs and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clips from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic communications through the website WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a trans woman and pioneering dissident whose conviction was overturned by Barack Obama when he had only three days left in office.
Dewey-Hagborg, by algorithmically analyzing the DNA that Manning extracted and creating 30 portraits of what someone might look like with this genomic data, has created a sharp, though somewhat intellectual, comment not only on the formability of DNA data -- the many ways it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations -- but also on identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has spoken openly about identifying as a woman since her adolescence, was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six counts of violating the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Prison had so suppressed her image that there was only one photo - a grainy, black-and-white selfie of Manning visibly uncomfortable in a driver's seat wearing a platinum-blond wig - that she was associated with.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was just coming off the big success of her 2012 project 'Stranger Visions'.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts like cigarette butts and gum, extracting the DNA from the waste to create a picture of what these people might look like.
That's when she got an e-mail from a newspaper magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted some sort of portrait to accompany this article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't visit at the time, and she couldn't be photographed, so you contacted Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to get a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became unequal correspondents, exchanging several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic book, "Suppressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which predicted a future in which the president would reverse Chelsea's judgment and she would be able to see the exhibition in person.
That Obama would actually, just days after the book was published, demand Manning's release after seven brutal years in a military prison in Kansas was a welcome sort of happy reunion.
There is something profound and powerful about the opening of the exhibition as Donald Trump wages a war against government informants and transgender troops to find new, two-way ways to further inflame the rigid divisions he was supposed to address.
When Dewey-Hagborg was asked about the strange timing of all these things, she said, "Things happen for a reason".
In an artistic statement engraved on the gallery wall, Manning, with her oversized signature below (the "i" in her family name is marked with a heart), demanded an end to "automatic fragmentation based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite wall is their mitochondrial DNA sequence -- a thousand feet of Cs and Gs and A's, written in pencil.
Dewey-Hagborg hoped that by including the 200 letters (or nucleotides in the artist's sophisticated scientific lexicon) to show how amazingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"What people will hopefully take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work Spurious Memories is also seen.
"DNA data can tell so many different stories, so here are 30 of them".
The last piece in the exhibition, which is kept in a private room, is a page from the comic book mentioned above.
It shows Manning emerging from the United States' disciplinary barracks like King Kong, with a pay phone in her hand.
"If they chill your speech, they've won", it says.
"So never shut up".
"It came straight from a letter she wrote me", said the artist, who greets from Philadelphia.
"I still get goose bumps when I talk about it".
Manning hasn't seen the exhibit in person yet -- as it was predictably predicted in the comic book -- but if she does, she'll be greeted in the middle of the room by the masks, by their own genomic simulators, who are swarming like hordes of protesters.
It was also targeted, like everything in the exhibition, down to the size (5'2, Manning's height), where their genetic haplogroups were written in pencil.
"In the past I had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd", Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted it to feel like a mass movement that was forming with Chelsea, like the movement that was also behind her liberation".
