"I find it so beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years", he says sadly.
"What a personal relationship, holding this letter in my hand".
A Castle in England spans the time from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era, documenting the families who lived in Scotney, each story illustrated by a different emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It's not Rhodes' first book to be based on an archive: he wrote Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
"I only reacted to the thumbprint on the page of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700s who worked for the Jacobins", he says.
"This is his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because back then, you lit a fire for the light.
For someone who lives 300 years later, the smell has the effect of being there himself.
Oh, I like the archives!"
For someone who is so beaten up by old papers that he is supported by the National Trust and Arts Council England and has lived in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I overestimated my welcome a little bit") all this seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, looking through the archives and studying the castle's many treasures and curiosities, such as the mounted hyenas' heads on the walls and the bottles that had been in the ditch for centuries.
He wandered through the grounds and the ruins of the old castle, talking to landscapers, gardeners, and sometimes even the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he drank whiskey and started writing.
Scotney's intimate history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not gain full access until 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the employees were just starting to take care of the archive, which he described as "hundreds of years of aristocrats saying, 'Oh, throw it in the attic.'
Diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You might think that land conflicts would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a birch that the two families fought over.
Boys, let it all go".
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to delve into wider English history, including 'The Labourer', which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot that took place in the castle in 1380, in this book entitled 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex'", says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising began in this area and I thought a rebellion would be a good start.
Maybe they're connected?"
Other stories are firmly rooted in the castle's history - like 'The Priest', which tells the story of the Jesuit father who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler,' which depicts 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell staging his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery that was not made until years later when his coffin was excavated).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favourite family of Scotney: "The gentlemen seemed to be quite crooks, continually taking on debts and spending money on things they could not afford.
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying rich old women - I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking guys with a talent for recruiting heirs".
After his time at the castle is over, Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experiences.
He has spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness for a comic novel about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th-century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave again", he says.
It was like, "Oh, now I have to get back to fucking life".
