Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may help to alleviate inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare to your digestive system.
But a new study claims just the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based proteins and dairy products could alleviate the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable condition, affecting some 1.3 million in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
While people are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan from proteins helps to develop immune cells that promote a tolerant gut.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells patrol the intestines to ensure that harmful microbes that are hidden in food do not enter the body.
Cells that are capable of causing inflammation are balanced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too far in the direction of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may result.
Experiments have shown that a type of tolerance-promoting immune cell is present in mice that carry a particular bacterium in their intestines.
And the bacteria needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to trigger the appearance of the cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a bacterial species - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their food, the more of these immune cells they had".
He suggested that the combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan promotes a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment if the same system works in humans.
Postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan was studying a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that one group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same strain, but housed separately, did not.
She suspected that the difference had to do with the gut microbiome of mice - the community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
So we sequenced the intestines of the mice, and we found six types of bacteria that were present in the mice with the immune cells, but were missing in the mice without them.
So mice were raised in a sterile environment, so they lacked a gut microbiome and they didn't develop that kind of immune cells, and they got the L. reuteri and the immune cells were created.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells evolved into the tolerance-promoting cells.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and that most of us protect against L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri develop the cells in humans as they do in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said, "The development of these cells is probably something we want to encourage, because these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the intestine.
Potentially, high tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri may lead to an expansion of this population.'
