The White House advertising costs the taxpayer thousands of dollars.
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn for an event highlighting American manufacturing last month costs taxpayers up to $24,000, according to the military's data, which was provided to TIME magazine.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One when the President is on board, was the centerpiece of the July 17 event at the White House with American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklifts from Mississippi.
The White House Military Office requested the presence of the helicopter in a fragmented order, or FRAGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I just wanted you to be aware of this because it's such an unusual event with high visibility", the commander of HMX-1 wrote to his superior, the deputy naval aviation commander, on the eve of the event.
The message indicated that the helicopter arrived on the South Lawn for the event at 3 p.m. on July 17 at about 7 a.m., and remained until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that evening.
The note adds that if the flight from the White House were to be delayed, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to the limitation of the hours of duty.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event, while the unit's security personnel remained on the ground with the aircraft during the event.
The records provided to TIME did not make it clear whether a second flight crew was ultimately needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 asked if the event might violate the designation.
"One question we asked was whether this was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that this was not the case", the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you're locked up", the deputy commander replied.
The "Made in America" event was designated by the White House as an official event and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave a boost to the health care reform reform that was underway in the Senate and he touted efforts to curb government regulations.
The use of the aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for political advantage is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are obliged to use it for travel.
But requiring it to be used only for a photo op is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane was providing taxi services against the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of reports complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is excited about the 'Made In America' show - which features products from all 50 states made by American workers with American materials", said White House deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often conduct training flights around Washington and the South Lawn to drop the President of the United States at the White House with precise centimeters.
When Trump was in Germany for the G20 summit in early July, HMX-1 performed 58 exercise landings at the White House.
The flight for the "Made in America" event was counted among the training needs of the flight crew for the month, an official said.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidential support missions".
The White House said that the taxpayers did not take the burden for any of the other props presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company had no involvement in the display of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for the presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
The Commission also notes that the US Department of Defense (DoD) has not provided any evidence that the VH-3D was a commercial aircraft.
Unit records show the plane's flight time as 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility's home base in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is far below that rate.
"It is highly misleading to determine the cost to taxpayers on the basis of estimates of the reimbursement rates", said Walters.
"These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs included in the annual appropriations".
According to a 2015 RAND study, the reimbursement rates for DoD do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance and contracting costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer was defending the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase things this week that are made in America", Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of their contribution to our national security, and I'm guessing that hundreds, if not thousands, of people depend on it.
And I think like most Americans, we're all proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly for.
It is, of course, appropriate to emphasize this".
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter as he entered his tour of the South Lawn for the event, but he sat in the driver's seat of a fire truck.
At the White House, Trump spoke to representatives of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky very well", said the President, "I have three of them".
