GMB's concern about investments in the McVitie plant in Glasgow
A union wants to check with the managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitie about the long-term commitment to production at their Glasgow plant.
GMB Scotland said the company had been silent about the future of investment at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work at the factory, which produces hobnobs and rich tea biscuits, among other products.
McVities owner Pladis said he's invested more than £5 million in the past few years.
He added that employees and trade union representatives would be 'the first to know' if their activities changed.
In a letter to the company's branch manager, GMB Scotland asked McVitie's to 'express concerns that funding for the modernisation of production lines is not being advanced'.
GMB Senior Organiser Drew Duffy said: "The fact that we cannot get any clarity from the General Site Manager about Tollcross's business needs and investment plans for the future is deeply affecting our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily focused on the local community and the Greater Glasgow area, an important pillar for decent employment in an area with high unemployment and social disadvantage.
Therefore, from the perspective of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising costs of living and chronic production decline, the east end of Glasgow urgently needs a thriving manufacturing presence at McVitie.'
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: 'The Tollcross branch manager received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday and the company will respond immediately as we appreciate the continued commitment from staff and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with employees and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, where some issues were openly discussed.
We discussed with the employees that, like all companies operating in a highly competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our business areas and locations - to remain competitive.
She added: 'Over the last few years we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise the heritage of Tollcross as a manufacturing site and if our operations change at the site, the employees and their union representatives will be the first to know".
Did PSG Barcelona warn you about Neymar three years ago?
The La Liga side may regret their interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not relent in their pursuit of Neymar after making a £189 million offer to trigger his release clause, but did they warn Barcelona of the world record heist three years ago?
