Interview: "Dompatzen report releases brother of the pope Georg Ratzinger"
The Regensburg Domspatzen report on the abuse cases exonerates the Pope's brother Georg Ratzinger.
So says author and historian Michael Hesemann.
The final report on the abuse scandal in the Regensburg Cathedral sparrows continues to generate discussion.
Christian Weisnder, spokesman for the reform movement "We are Church", told the German press agency after the publication that he expects an apology from the former bishop of Regensburg and current Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller and from the cathedral choirmaster Georg Ratzinger, the 93-year-old brother of retired Pope Benedict XVI.
It would be very good for the reputation of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger expressed their deep regret over their own omissions or their then wrong assessment of events.
The Vatican newspaper Osservatore Romano, on the other hand, criticized the "double standard" of reporting on violence among the bishops.
Regarding the attacks in Regensburg, no one doubts that they are "disgraceful and shameful acts" that should be punished and prevented in the future, but the "degree of media manipulation" is striking, says author Lucetta Scaraffia, historian and member of the Italian National Bioethics Committee.
"The practice of calling the Catholic Church the source of all evil is already part of everyday life and prepares public opinion to accept it as normal", writes Scaraffia.
Princess Gloria of Thurn and Taxis also said in an interview with the Bavarian Radio: "You like to go to church and that's a found food".
She also noted that in her youth "beating was a normal educational tool" "to deal with naughty children like myself".
She would find it unfair to apply today's standards to earlier decades, because the world has changed.
In connection with reports of abuse, Brother Georg Ratzinger, the pope, often appeared.
Quite wrong, says author and historian Michael Hesemann, who wrote the memoir "My Brother the Pope" (translated into 12 languages) with Ratzinger.
"I have to protect Georg Ratzinger", says Hesemann, "because all this had nothing to do with him", he assesses the results of the final report.
What exactly is stated in the 440-page report submitted by the lawyer Ulrich Weber, who was commissioned by the Diocese of Regensburg to investigate the matter?
A total of 547 Regensburg Dom sparrows were "highly plausible" victims of assault between 1945 and the early 1990s, 67 Dom sparrows were sexually abused.
The final report says of Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994: "In summary, it can be stated that in many cases forms of physical and psychological violence were used by Domkapellmeister R.
It was especially when the students were highly emotional that the punishment for them could be more severe.
Nevertheless, unlike many other defendants, it is noteworthy that many victims appreciated R.'s general humanity and therefore in many cases, despite the violence, even associate positive memories with him".
In the interview, Hesemann explains why the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg Domspatzen exonerates Georg Ratzinger in his opinion.
Mr Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "incidents of violence against protective officers at the Regensburg Cathedral" gives a contradictory picture of Cathedral Chapel Master Georg Ratzinger.
For one thing, many students emphasize his "humanity".
On the other hand, he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist, who often became a handyman when a dom sparrow did not bring top performance musically.
As his biographer, how do you rate this final report?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble to read the entire 440-page report from cover to cover, you'd rather wonder why the name Georg Ratzinger is even in it.
It is only eight pages long and it is clearly cleared of any suspicion of complicity or knowledge in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The violence at the preschool was also outside its sphere of influence.
He may be accused of not knowing it too late or of not taking the first hints seriously enough.
The Domspatz Gymnasium, where he worked, was perceived by virtually all respondents as - so literally - "salvation", "heaven", and "a better world".
Thus the vast majority of Georg Ratzinger's students give him a very excellent testimony, describing him as "warm-hearted", "loved", "sincere", "competent", and "understanding", as an extremely kind-hearted teacher who regularly supplied the boys with cakes, cookies, and candies and who was "always surrounded by grapes from children".
Only a minority complain about his perfectionism and his high emotionality, which has led to outbursts of anger.
That he not only smashed chairs and threw the key chain on the floor, but also slapped and pulled the hair or ears of too-proud boys, he himself admitted years ago, deeply regretting it and apologizing.
However, it must be said in his honour that such methods of education were widespread in the 1960s and 1970s, both among parents and teachers.
Do you know any other methods of punishment?
Of course, I think any of us born before 1968.
I too experienced this in a secular school, a state high school.
I am sure that the Commission will be able to give us a clearer picture of the situation in the Member States.
One wonders if it's not more about his fame and his role as brother to Benedict XVI that many media are rushing to him.
Many who have never understood the Bavarian pope are still eager to work on him.
The truth is that the report absolves Georg Ratzinger in every respect.
The report has been widely reported in the media on the subject of abuse of the Regensburg House sparrows.
Does the final report also accuse Georg Ratzinger of any involvement or knowledge of sexual abuse?
Michael Hesemann: Clearly not.
Not one of the 67 victims of sexual assault claims to have confided in the choirmaster.
Not even the parents were initiated.
"I never dared to talk to my father or mother about it", said one sufferer, speaking for the others, "because I was very embarrassed about it".
The real problem with the education of sexual abuse was and is that most victims remain silent out of shame.
If they did not confide in their parents and siblings, they certainly did not confide in a choirmaster who was, in a sense, a colleague of the perpetrators.
How do the Domspatzen students evaluate Ratzinger's role in the abuse cases?
Michael Hesemann: One student interviewed put it this way: "In the case of sexual abuse ... I don't see ... any case where he (Georg Ratzinger) alone had timely knowledge and could have stopped the perpetrator.
I think it's... also really absurd to assume that it's him... that boys have been more intrusive or clearer or even more open than their parents, their boarding school teachers, their trust teachers, etc.
"That you talk to him about sex is unthinkable".
The report concludes that "it was not possible to confirm that the affected pupils and/or their environment had confided in him beforehand".
So, as far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger is to be exonerated of all knowledge.
So he cannot be accused of not preventing or reporting it.
So there is no reason to associate his good name with these heinous crimes, as has unfortunately happened in some cases.
The media have been reading a lot about "violent taxation" among the Domspatzen of Regensburg.
The former cathedral choirmaster Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report "Wegschauen".
Does he have to live with that?
Michael Hesemann: That's the big problem, that in the reporting, everything is mixed and mixed into a huge mix of sexual abuse and violence and somewhere in the middle, Georg Ratzinger.
But that is precisely what the report is doing wrong.
The Commission has not yet decided whether to accept the amendments tabled by the Committee on Budgets.
The report also covers incidents from 1945 onwards, including four decades during which Georg Ratzinger was not the choir leader of the Domspats.
The whole terrible school-beating, the cases of boys being harassed and mistreated by sadistic teachers and suffering horribly, all took place in the kindergartens in Etterhausen and Pielenhofen, where conditions must have been truly scandalous.
But the choirmaster of the cathedral, Georg Ratzinger, had nothing to do with them, for he did not see the boys until they were in the cathedral's grammar school.
Most witnesses point out that the subject of "preschool" was taboo.
They were just happy to have escaped it and enjoyed so much better treatment and, for many, even "paradise" conditions.
What was different about the Domspatz Gymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but no sadistic violence.
This is also true of Georg Ratzinger, who concludes that "many victims appreciated R.'s general humanity and therefore, in many cases, despite the violence, even associate positive memories with him".
At most, the blame remains for having looked away.
However, despite all efforts, the report was only able to define two periods during which it was informed of conditions in the preschool.
The first time was in 1970/71, when he was just starting to establish himself and refused to hear about the proceedings at a school where he was not acting and responsible (so the witness said), and then again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently turn a deaf ear to the situation?
Michael Hesemann: No, because back in 1989 he wrote a letter to the headmaster of the Dompatz Gymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
In it he warns him that "the practice of flogging is still practiced in preschool".
Even in the face of the danger of negative press releases, he recommended urgent action.
This was, of course, at a time when there was legal clarity, when flogging had long been prohibited in Bavaria.
Before that, they took place in a legal gray area, as we all know.
It was also difficult for him to determine where the parties concerned might have exaggerated or dramatized and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can't say he's always looked the other way.
That's just not true.
It was not until 1980 that the punishment of school flogging was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria of Thurn and Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today's educational standards to the time.
How do you see it?
Michael Hesemann: We historians are talking about the "trap of anachronism", the danger of judging the past by today's moral standards.
The princess is right.
But this does not apply to sexual abuse, which has always been abhorrent, nor to the atrocities and violence committed in preschools against innocent children, which is far beyond what was usual at the time.
This is all very awful and I'm glad it's finally being worked out.
But at the same time, I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because all this had nothing to do with him.
His methods of discipline and punishment, such as slapping and pulling on the hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When corporal punishment was outlawed, he strictly adhered to it.
What picture of his Regensburg days did Georg Ratzinger give in his talks with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Was the subject of flogging mentioned?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, Pope Benedict XVI, told from his perspective, where the bishops played only a secondary role.
But I'm not hiding the fact that he was in charge of a strict regiment.
But it must also be said that without this perfectionism, without the demand for unconditional discipline, it would have been hardly possible for him to turn the then nationally renowned Regensburg Cathedral into an institution of world-class importance, a true cultural ambassador for Europe and its musical tradition, which toured twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With cookies and candy alone, you can't make a bad boy into a great singer. And you can't beat success in any field, but always discipline, passion and self-improvement.
What kind of person did you see Georg Ratzinger during the talks on your book?
Michael Hesemann: Through the work on the book and beyond, I got to know Georg Ratzinger really well and I saw him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, thorough, deeply religious and kind-hearted person, one who you can't imagine could do anything to a fly.
I regularly hear how many former parishioners still have regular contact with him, visit him, read to him - he's almost blind - and treat him like a member of their family, 23 years after he retired.
So those who still don't forgive him for being so hard on them are clearly in the minority.
Most of the dummies are grateful to him for enriching their lives and bringing them closer to the world of music.
And that he was always a good fatherly teacher - a strict father, of course - but also a lovable and respected person whom they still look up to and worship.
And, again, I want to be clear: all the accusations against him are the methods of parenting that were the norm at the time.
We can be glad that we have long since passed this time.
But it's extremely unfair to make a man, just because he's prominent and has an even more prominent brother, a media scapegoat.
The evil intent behind it is all too obvious.
Because the report that has just been published relieves him of his duties.
Now decency would order a 93-year-old man who has acquired great merits and without the outside Bavaria and perhaps even Germany probably no one would know the Regensburg Domspatzen, finally leave in peace.
